        q: "Structured concurrency in Kotlin",
        en: "What?\n\n**Structured concurrency** means every coroutine has a parent **Job** in a **CoroutineScope** — work is organized as a tree, not fire-and-forget globals. When a scope is cancelled, all children cancel. Errors and completion propagate predictably.\n\nKey scopes on Android:\n- `viewModelScope` — tied to ViewModel clear\n- `lifecycleScope` — tied to Lifecycle destroy\n- `rememberCoroutineScope()` — tied to Composable leave\n- `coroutineScope { }` / `supervisorScope { }` — structured blocks inside a function\n\nWhy?\n\nInfosys Day 3 topic: explain **scope + dispatchers + launch/async** together.\n- **launch**: no result, returns Job\n- **async**: Deferred result, await in same parent scope\n- **Dispatchers.Main / IO / Default**: where work runs\n- Avoid **GlobalScope** — breaks structure, leaks after UI gone\n\n`coroutineScope` — if one child fails, all siblings cancel. `supervisorScope` — one child failure does not cancel siblings (use with care + error handling).\n\nHow?\n\nInterview sentence: “I launch work in viewModelScope on IO for Repository calls, expose StateFlow on Main, and when the user leaves the screen the Job tree cancels so network/Room work stops — that is structured concurrency.”",
        hi: "What?\n\nStructured concurrency = har coroutine ka parent scope/Job. Scope cancel → saare child cancel. GlobalScope mat use karo.\n\nWhy?\n\nviewModelScope, lifecycleScope Android standard. launch side effect, async parallel result await.\n\nMain UI, IO network/Room, Default heavy CPU.\n\ncoroutineScope fail par sab cancel. supervisorScope ek fail par baaki chal sakte.\n\nHow?\n\nEk sentence practice: viewModelScope + Dispatchers.IO + StateFlow — screen band par kaam ruk jata hai."
