        en: "What?\n\nlateinit var must be var, non-null, and assigned before first read — typically in onCreate, inject, or init block. Used for lateinit ViewBinding, NavController, or Hilt @Inject lateinit fields. Reading before init throws UninitializedPropertyAccessException.\n\nWhy?\n\nlazy delegates initialization until first access — thread-safe by default (LazyThreadSafetyMode.SYNCHRONIZED). Returns T, not nullable. Ideal for expensive one-time setup: Gson, Retrofit instance, encrypted prefs wrapper.\n\nlateinit cannot hold primitives; lazy can. lazy is val semantics — computed once (unless LazyThreadSafetyMode.NONE in single-thread context).\n\nAndroid: prefer by viewModels(), by lazy { ViewBinding.inflate() } in Fragment carefully (view lifecycle). For DI, constructor injection beats lateinit when possible.\n\nHow?\n\nInterview: lateinit risk on process death — if not re-set after restore, crash. lazy survives as long as holder object lives.",
